datastring.name: Summary
datastring.dstemplatestring:
B.5.1 Narrative Include Clinical

This spontaneous report from a consumer was received by Jazz Pharmaceuticals, Inc. (2014-US-007676) on 17-Jun-2014 and was forwarded
to UCB on 25-Jun-2014. This was a report for the occurrence of weight decrease in an adult male patient from United States who was presc
ribed Xyrem (sodium oxybate) oral solution, for the indication of narcolepsy. In Sep-2013, the patient initiated sodium oxybate (500mg/ml)
via oral, at a dose of 2.25 g, twice nightly. After dose adjustments, his most recent dose was 4.5 g twice nightly. From an unknown date, the
patient had lost 52 kg of weight. At the time of this report, the event of lost 52 kg was not resolved and sodium oxybate therapy was continu
ed. Spontaneous report from consumer/other non health professional. Adult male patient experienced weight loss of 52 kg after the initiation
of sodium oxybate. Therapy with sodium oxybate was continued and the event was ongoing. Follow up information was received by Jazz pha
rmaceuticals from a nurse practitioner on 30-Jul-2014 and was forwarded to UCB on 07-Aug-2014. The stop date of 2.25g twice nightly dosin
g regimen was updated to 2013. From an unknown date in 2013 to an unknown date in 2013, dose adjustments were made and currently the
patient was on 4.5g twice nightly dose, initiated on an unknown date in 2013. The reporter medically confirmed the event of weight loss of 1
15 pounds. The reporter clarified that the weight loss was intentional and not related to sodium oxybate therapy. Follow up information was r
eceived by Jazz Pharmaceuticals from the consumer on 21-Nov-2014 and was forwarded to UCB on 26-Nov-2014. This case concerns an ad
ult male patient (currently 41-years-old). Upon follow-up, the event of lost 52 kg was updated to lost 56.7kg. The events of decreased blood p
ressure of 100/60, dreaming more, takes 1 milligram (mg) of Clonazepam at 9 P.M. every night and takes sodium oxybate at midnight, increas
ed his dose to 3.75 g followed by 4.5 g (intentional dose increase) were added. Relevant medical history of high blood pressure and vivid dre
ams were added. Concomitant medications of Dyazide (hydrochlorothiazide and triamterene) and benazepril were added. Previously, the pati
ent experienced worsening vivid dreams (reported in 2013-US-001935). From unspecified date in 2013 to unspecified date in 2014, the patie
